Like most daily choices, alcohol consumption has various pros and cons. On the one hand, it can be a social catalyst, associated with fun times and good memories. On the other hand, excessive alcohol consumption is also among those unhealthy lifestyle choices that remain leading causes of death and disease across many Western European and North American countries (\cite{oecd_avoidable_2016}). In line with this ambiguity, diverse stakeholders, from alcohol brands to public health officials, have strong interests in influencing alcohol consumption. Research shows that persuasive messages from both sides impact drinking decisions (\cite{jernigan_alcohol_2017,young_effectiveness_2018}). The complexity of the information environment surrounding alcohol and other issues like it makes it exceedingly difficult to predict the effects of any given persuasive message targeting related behaviors or attitudes. Understanding to what extent and why health promotion messages such as anti-alcohol messaging outperform health-harming competitors may significantly improve our ability to design effective health communication. Across two empirical studies, we describe the effects of professional anti-alcohol information in the context of it's real-world competitors (professional and peer-produced pro- and anti-alcohol information). We further examine diverse emotional responses and familiarity as key mechanisms of these effects. [CONTRIBUTION]

\subsection{The Alcohol Information Environment}
Once any persuasive message is released to it's target group, it enters rich information environments (e.g. on social media) which include other content produced by professionals or peers that is relevant to the same decision (e.g. alcohol consumption) and may or may not be in line with the original message (\cite{hendriks_social_2018, stautz_immediate_2016, young_effectiveness_2018}). 

For instance, in the context of alcohol, pro-alcohol information, that is information about positive consequences of alcohol consumption, is distributed by both professional alcohol marketers and peers. Alcohol marketing has been shown to increase purchase and drinking behavior (\cite{jernigan_alcohol_2017}). In addition, alcohol consumption is strongly driven by social influences from peers [CITES] who are known to overwhelmingly talk positively about alcohol to each other \cite{scholz_neural_2019, hendriks_what_2015} and post about positive consequences of drinking on social media (\cite{hendriks_social_2018}). Similarly, anti-alcohol information is distributed by professionals (e.g. policy makers and organizations such as universities) and peers (e.g. narratives about negative drinking experiences).

Overall, research indicates that exposure to information about alcohol is frequent and overwhelmingly pro-alcohol. Nevertheless, arguments against alcohol consumption tend to be well known by many, creating a state of ambiguity. How do we make decisions about drinking within this complex environment?

\subsection{Decisions in Complex Information Environments}

Prior work has theorized and demonstrated that the effects of multiple sources of influence on the same decision interfere with each other. For instance, social interactions that derogate a mass media campaign message can cause unexpected boomerang effects and responses to anti-alcohol campaigns interact with pro-alcohol peer influence to impact alcohol consumption (David et al., 2006; Katz, 1957; Scholz et al., 2019; Southwell & Yzer, 2007). Similarly, a comprehensive theoretical model of cognitive and psychological mechanisms that support the integration of multiple sources of influence on consumption decisions and, therefore, a reliable way to predict persuasive message effects in real life remains missing. 

