\subsection{Current Study}
- We ran 3 online studies (called Study 1a, 1b, 2) to examine differential and cumulative effects of different types of alcohol-related information on craving for alcohol and to explore mechanisms of these effects
- Study 1a: Exposure to 12 pieces of alcohol-related information in within-person experiment: professional vs. peer-produced sources, pro- vs. anti-alcohol valence, Instagram post vs. Google search result, measures of drinking urge after exposure as well as potential mechanisms (emotional responses, familiarity with depicted situations)
- Study 1b: Exposure to 12 pieces of information: info about non-alcoholic drinks vs. alcohol-related information (sub-sample of study 1a stimuli), measures of drinking urge after exposure as well as potential mechanisms (emotional responses, familiarity with depicted situations)
- Study 2: Exposure to all alcohol-related types of information (88 trials per person/22 per condition), followed by exposure to a standardized alcohol cue (e.g. a beer bottle) and drinking urge rating
- Context: All analyses are exploratory (i.e. not pre-registered).

\section{Method}
Two online studies in independent samples were conducted to examine the effects of valence and source characteristics of Instagram posts about alcohol on the urge to consume alcohol in young adults.

\subsection{Stimuli}
A set of 120 manipulated stimuli were created for Study 1, of which 88 were chosen and re-tested in Study 2. Stimuli consisted of an alcohol-related image and a hashtag which were both entered into one of two templates, a template mimicking an Instagram post (used for all Study 1 stimuli and half of the Study 2 stimuli) or a template mimicking the result of a Google search (used only in Study 2; see Figure 1A)\footnote{The two templates were introduced for an exploratory research question. None of the results discussed here are influenced by template.}. Stimuli were designed to manipulate two experimental factors, valence and source. 

To manipulate valence, we chose pro-alcohol images which showed alcohol or alcohol consumption in a positive context (e.g. portraying positive outcomes of drinking) and a set of anti-alcohol images which portrayed alcohol or alcohol consumption in a negative context (e.g. showing negative outcomes of drinking). Post source was manipulated by choosing pro- and anti-alcohol images from public Instagram accounts of everyday users, namely images with relatively few likes at the time of sampling that were not posted by a professional organization, business, or influencer account, or from a professional source. Professional pro-alcohol images were sampled from professional Instagram accounts of businesses and brands (e.g. bars and alcohol brands) and include marketing materials for specific types of alcohol and alcohol-related, branded events. Professional anti-alcohol images were taken from global, English-language public health campaigns advocating against (excessive) drinking, derived from an online search. Figure 1B shows example images per experimental condition.

Any comments or hashtags on the original sampled Instagram posts were removed and replaced with standardized hashtags that match the condition in question. The goal of creating these hashtags was to standardize the amount of text shown in each condition and to clearly identify each image as related to alcohol. For peer-produced posts, we sampled hashtags that are frequently used on Instagram for the types of images used in this study (e.g. [EXAMPLES]). For professional pro-alcohol posts, we used hashtags communicating brand names (e.g. #baccardi). For professional anti-alcohol stimuli we used hashtags related to the content of the campaigns, often the campaign slogan (e.g. #EXAMPLE).

